Configuring GIT
In windows use gitBash/ In mac use terminal to run these commands.
# git config --global user.name "My Name"
# git config --global user.email "someone@email.com"
# git config --list
~ --> root directory

In Git, configuration settings can be stored at different levels.

The two most commonly used are:

Global configuration
Local configuration

*  Global Configuration  *

Global configuration applies to all repositories of your system/user account.
When you set username or email globally, every Git project will use it by default.
*  Local Configuration  *

Local configuration applies to only one specific repository.

Useful when:

Different GitHub accounts are used
Office and personal emails differ
Team requires specific identity

Clone & Status
Clone - Cloning a repository on our local machine. Copying folder from github to local system
# git clone <--some link--> // This link we will get from our repository in https

Status - displays the state of the code
# git status
clear command to clear the terminal
ls: - list files in git
ls -a: - list all hidden files in git

When a file is modified then we have to add and commit 
Four status of files
Untracked :- new files that git doesn't track yet.
Modified :- Changed
Staged :- file is ready to committed
Unmodified :- unchanged

Add:- Add new or changed files in your working directory to the git staging area.
#  git add <--file name-->
#  git add . // Add all files at once

Commit:- It is the record of change
#  git commit -m "some message"

When we commit changes but the changes are not shown on the github then we use the Push command

Push:- Upload local repo content to remote repo
#  git push origin main

